{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01484zxhqBjqXY6sRySwXYar","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture:\n\n1. Current server cert expires **June 28, 2026** (in ~2 days) - it's nearing expiry\n2. The cert covers SANs: localhost, mongo, mongo.mongodb, mongo.mongodb.svc, mongo.mongodb.svc.cluster.local, and all 3 replica pod FQDNs\n3. MongoDB uses `requireTLS` mode with `/etc/mongo-cert/server.pem` (cert+key) and `/etc/mongo-ca/ca.crt`\n4. The `mongodb-tls-cert` secret stores the cert and private key together, and Kubernetes automatically syncs secret updates to mounted volumes within 1-2 minutes\n5. MongoDB 6.0 supports the `rotateCertificates` admin command for hot-reloading certificates without downtime\n\nSo the approach is to generate a new cert, update the secret, wait for the kubelet to propagate it, then trigger the rotation command on MongoDB. So the concrete steps are: generate a new certificate signed by the same CA, update the secret with the new cert+key pair, let Kubernetes propagate the volume mount changes, then run the `rotateCertificates` admin command on each MongoDB pod to hot-reload without downtime. Since the cluster allows connections without certificates, I have some flexibility here. Let me work through the implementation.\n\nFor the SANs, I need to match what's already in the existing cert - localhost, mongo, the full DNS names for the service, and the individual pod FQDNs across all three replicas.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1556,"cache_read_input_tokens":44303,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1556},"output_tokens":29,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"1509cf16-f0a0-4451-a8fe-589db5e6b650","u